abstract = {Computer models designed to simulate the dynamics of a forest by following the fates of each individual tree in a forest stand were created initially in the mid-1960s. The earliest such model was built by Newnham (1964), followed by similar developments in several Schools of Forestry in the US. These early models involved using a digital computer to dynamically change a map of the sizes and positions of each tree in a simulated forest. Importantly, these initial models were as complex and detailed as their present day descendants. With increased computing power becoming cheap and available, applications using these models have become increasingly frequent (Shugart and West, 1980). Gap models simulate the changes in a small patch of forest on the order of 0.1 ha in size. The models project the annual growth of each individual tree on the patch as well as the death of each tree and the regeneration of new individual trees. Gap models are important because of their widespread applications in assessing the effects of environmental change on forests. The models have been applied to develop theories about the overall functioning of forested landscape and have also been used to reconstruct the composition of forests of the past and under future conditions. Gap models are a special case of the more general individual-based models. They have been used particularly for forest ecosystems. Because gap models have been applied in a very wide range of ecosystems, often the term, gap model, is used interchangeably with other individual-based model when applied to mix age and multi-species ecosystems. The models simulate landscapes as dynamically changing mosaics with each element of the mosaic having an interactive population of trees of different species and sizes. Output from the models resembles field data as sampled from a standard forest survey unit: a list of the diameters of each tree (and its species) alive on the patch for each year. These model data can be transformed to estimates of biomass (and hence, net production), leaf area profiles through the canopy, and tree ring histories for each trees.},
