@article{Wagner2015,
abstract = {I would like to thank Emerson et al. (2015) for providing a more formal description and clarification of spatial component regression (SCR). Indeed, their comment goes beyond the scope of the original paper and provides a much-needed analysis of the perfor-mance of constrained SCR, a variation of spatial filtering with spatial eigenvectors using Moran eigen-vector maps (MEM), in regression inference. The simulation results clearly show that spatial filtering, as implemented in Wagner (2013), does not control type I errors. While the original paper did not explicitly make such a claim, it did not explicitly warn that the behavior has not been thoroughly tested yet, hence Emerson et al. provide a timely warning. Previous studies testing spatial filtering methods with eigenvectors have reported conflicting results. For instance, Beale et al. (2010) found spatial filtering did not control type I error rates, whereas Peres-Neto and Legendre (2010) found that spatial filtering did control type I error rates. Clearly, more research is urgently needed to understand under which conditions spatial filtering effectively controls for type I error rates, and to what degree this performance depends on the definition of the spatial weights matrix. On the other hand, the goal of Wagner (2013) was not to advocate a fully developed, specific method, but to challenge present thinking: the main message being that spatial eigenvectors provide a partitioning of regression models whose potential has not been fully recognized yet because of the narrow focus on variation partitioning and spatial filtering. Rather than selecting a small set of spatial eigenvectors, we can gain new insights by examining the association of the data with the full set of spatial eigenvectors. Expressing the correlation r xy between two variables x and y as the product of two vectors r yV and r xV of correlations with a matrix of spatial eigenvectors V thus leads to interesting new avenues. Applications may include spectral randomiza-tion methods for irregularly spaced and multivariate data or the development of diagnostic tools for spatial regression analysis. Finally, spatial weights matrices that are not of full rank need further attention in MEM and SCR. These matrices will result in multiple zero eigenvalues (or close to zero), but dropping them will lead to a matrix V with eigenvectors V k that do not fulfill the equation R k r 2},
